# Difference between JPA, Hibernate and Spring Data JPA

## What is JPA?

- JPA (Java Persistence API) is a specification for Object Relational Mapping (ORM).
- It defines a standard way to map Java objects to database tables.
- JPA itself does not provide an implementation.
- Example: EntityManager, @Entity, @Id.

## What is Hibernate?

- Hibernate is an implementation of the JPA specification.
- It provides the actual ORM functionality.
- Hibernate converts Java objects into database records and vice versa.
- It generates SQL queries automatically.

## What is Spring Data JPA?

- Spring Data JPA is a Spring Framework module built on top of JPA.
- It reduces boilerplate code by providing repository interfaces.
- By extending JpaRepository, developers get CRUD operations without writing implementation code.
- It internally uses a JPA implementation such as Hibernate.

## Relationship

JPA (Specification)
        ↓
Hibernate (Implementation)
        ↓
Spring Data JPA (Repository Abstraction)
        ↓
Application

## Comparison

| Feature | JPA | Hibernate | Spring Data JPA |
|---------|-----|-----------|-----------------|
| Type | Specification | JPA Implementation | Spring Module |
| Purpose | Defines ORM rules | Implements ORM | Simplifies database access |
| SQL Generation | No | Yes | Uses Hibernate internally |
| CRUD Operations | Manual | Manual | Automatic using JpaRepository |
| Dependency | Requires implementation | Can work independently | Depends on JPA and Hibernate |

## Conclusion

- JPA defines the standard for ORM.
- Hibernate implements the JPA specification.
- Spring Data JPA simplifies database operations by using JPA and Hibernate internally, reducing boilerplate code and providing easy CRUD functionality.
